# 2️⃣ OOP Basics — Encapsulation & Abstraction

These are VERY frequently asked in interviews.

---

# First Understand the Big Idea

OOP tries to model real-world systems.

Main goals:

* security
* organization
* simplicity

---

# A. Encapsulation

---

## Simple Idea

👉 Wrapping data + functions together.

AND

👉 Hiding data from direct misuse.

---

## Real-World Example

ATM machine.

You can:

* withdraw money
* check balance

But you CANNOT directly access:

```text id="0w5v4d"
bank database
```

Hidden internally.

---

# Example

```cpp id="7e84ui"
class Bank
{
private:
    int balance = 5000;

public:

    void showBalance()
    {
        cout << balance;
    }
};
```

---

# What Happens?

`balance` is hidden using:

```cpp id="q0v46z"
private
```

Access only through functions.

---

# Why Encapsulation Matters

Without it:

```cpp id="ylryg0"
balance = -100000;
```

Invalid data ❌

Encapsulation protects data.

---

# Mental Model

```text id="jjlwmu"
Capsule → data protected inside
```

---

# How to Remember

```text id="nlz4y3"
Encapsulation = data hiding + control
```

---

# B. Abstraction

---

## Simple Idea

👉 Show only important things.
Hide complex implementation.

---

## Real-World Example

Driving a car.

You know:

* steering
* brake
* accelerator

But not:

* engine internals
* combustion system

Hidden complexity.

---

# Example

```cpp id="4khvse"
class Car
{
public:

    void start()
    {
        cout << "Car Started";
    }
};
```

User only calls:

```cpp id="jlwm7m"
start()
```

Internal complexity hidden.

---

# Why Abstraction Matters

Without abstraction:

* systems become too complex

With abstraction:

* easier to use

---

# Mental Model

```text id="xmsjlwm"
Abstraction = hide complexity
```

---

# Difference Between Encapsulation & Abstraction

| Encapsulation                   | Abstraction           |
| ------------------------------- | --------------------- |
| protects data                   | hides complexity      |
| security focus                  | simplicity focus      |
| achieved using access modifiers | achieved using design |

